1336 For award payments to licensed physicians or nurse practitioners who agree to practice
1337 full-time in primary care in a medically underserved rural area for an agreed upon number of
1338 years. No payment shall be allowed for a physician or nurse practitioner who has practiced
1339 within three years of October 1, 2026, in a primary care service area with a deficit, or
1340 surplus of less than 2.0 primary-care physicians, as shown by the most-recent Status Report of
1341 the Alabama Primary Care Physician Workforce from the Office for Family Health Education &
1342 Research at the UAB Huntsville Regional Medical Campus. The Office of Primary Care and Rural
1343 Health may pay an eligible physician or nurse practitioner as much as $50,000 a year for each
1344 year of service, in a medically underserved rural area, agreed to by contract by the physician
1345 or nurse practitioner, but any payment shall be for no more than three years. Contracts shall
1346 set out refund and penalty requirements for failure by a physician or nurse practitioner to
1347 meet the contract terms. A medically underserved rural area as determined by the Office shall
1348 be: (1) in a rural primary care service area with a deficit of primary-care physicians as shown
1349 by the most recent Status Report of the Alabama Primary Care Physician Workforce, and (2) in a
1350 county in which no more than two physicians have worked or are scheduled to be working within
1351 12 months to repay a loan awarded by the Alabama Board of Medical Scholarship Awards. The
1352 Office shall file a report with the Chairs of the Senate Committee on Finance and
1353 Taxation-General Fund and the House Ways and Means-General Fund Committee, the Legislative
1354 Fiscal Officer and the Finance Director by October 15, 2027, on how the money was spent in
1355 fiscal year 2027 and the names of participants and where they agreed to practice or were
1356 practicing in return for payments from the Office.
